# --- Supabase JS client (HTTPS) — PostgREST, Auth, Storage, Realtime ---
# Project Settings → API: Project URL + anon (legacy) or publishable key.
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL="https://YOUR_PROJECT_REF.supabase.co"
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY="your-anon-or-publishable-key"

# --- Drizzle / pg (Postgres wire protocol on port 5432) ---
# Still required for migrations, db:push, and server SQL via Drizzle — not replaceable by the URL above.
# Postgres — Supabase: Project Settings → Database → Connection string → URI
#
# NOT the https://xxx.supabase.co project URL — must be postgres:// or postgresql://
#
# Paste whatever Supabase shows as the full URI. Valid shapes include:
#   postgresql://...   or   postgres://...     (same thing for Node/pg)
#   ...@HOST:5432/DATABASE_NAME
#
# The last segment is the database name — on Supabase it is usually "postgres" (default DB).
# If your string has no leading scheme, add: postgresql://
# If your string has no /database at the end, append: /postgres (unless Supabase names it differently)
#
# For drizzle-kit, prefer the DIRECT connection (port 5432), not Transaction pool (6543).
# sslmode / connect_timeout are added automatically in code if missing.
#
# Do NOT keep [YOUR-PASSWORD] or any [ ] brackets — those are docs placeholders only.
# Paste the full URI from Supabase “Copy”, or put the real password with no brackets.
#
# If your password contains @, #, etc., it must be URL-encoded in the URI (@ → %40).
# Or always use Supabase “Copy” on the connection string so encoding is correct.
#
# Optional — if the password has @ or is awkward to embed in the URI:
#   DATABASE_URL=postgresql://postgres@db.YOUR_PROJECT_REF.supabase.co:5432/postgres
#   DATABASE_PASSWORD=your raw password (any characters; do not quote unless your tool requires it)
# The app and drizzle-kit merge DATABASE_PASSWORD with encoding via resolveDatabaseUrl().
#
# If you see ECONNREFUSED to an IPv6 address (2600:...), the app prefers IPv4 DNS order;
# if issues persist, try another network or Supabase’s pooler URI from the dashboard.
#
# Example (replace USER, PASSWORD, HOST, DB with your values):
DATABASE_URL="postgres://USER:PASSWORD@HOST:5432/DB"

# --- Auth (Supabase) ---
# Enable Email provider: Supabase Dashboard → Authentication → Providers → Email.
# Create a test user: Authentication → Users → Add user (or sign up from /login if sign-ups enabled).
# Run SQL migrations in order through 013 (see supabase/migrations/): 001–008 baseline;
# 009 directory fields; 010 smart groups; 011 employee UPDATE RLS; 012 schedule jobs/groups/shifts;
# 013 shift layers (Connecteam-style metadata).
#
# Dev login (optional): create user in Supabase Auth with:
#   Email:    dev@retailhr.local
#   Password: DevPassword123!
# The login page pre-fills these in `next dev` only.
#
# Auth gate is currently OFF (middleware does not redirect to /login). Dashboard uses the anon key.
# If rows fail to load, run supabase/migrations/004_anon_read_dev_no_auth_gate.sql in the SQL Editor.
#
# When you're ready to require login again:
#   NEXT_PUBLIC_AUTH_ENABLED=true
#   (and restore `lib/supabase/middleware.ts` redirect logic + tighten RLS as needed)
#
# Optional: force dashboard to use only mock data (no Supabase queries on the home page).
# When true, KPIs show fixed demo totals (e.g. ~318 employees for “All locations”) — turn OFF for real DB/MVP.
#   NEXT_PUBLIC_USE_MOCK_DATA=true
#
# Role-based access (server-side): map `employees.role` → permissions in `lib/rbac/matrix.ts`.
# Requires a signed-in user whose email matches `employees.email`. When enabled, unauthenticated
# visits to the app shell redirect to /login.
#   RBAC_ENABLED=true
#
# --- MVP demo (stakeholder walkthrough) ---
# Recommended for demos: leave RBAC_ENABLED unset, use real Supabase data, migrations 001→013.
# Optional: show a dashboard ribbon so recordings don’t look like “prod”.
#   NEXT_PUBLIC_MVP_DEMO=true
# Or run: npm run dev:demo
#
# See DEMO.md for a short checklist.
